benchmark_config.jira_title: Implement/Test API: GET /1.0/kb/admin/queues - Get queues entries

covered: Valid request flows: default and parameterized successful retrievals are exercised (TC01-TC10, TC23).
Query parameter coverage: accountId, queueName, serviceName, minDate/maxDate, withHistory, withInProcessing, withBusEvents, withNotifications are tested (TC02-TC09, TC05).
Combined filters and partial input handling are covered (TC10, TC23).
Empty and no-match responses are covered (TC11, TC29).
Account ID error handling: invalid format -> 400 and not found -> 404 are tested (TC13, TC14).
Authorization negative case (missing/invalid token -> 401) is covered (TC15).
Service and server error handling: 503, 500, timeout (504), and transient recovery are tested (TC16, TC30, TC19, TC27).
Security tests: injection and XSS scenarios are present (TC17, TC26).
Performance and scalability: large data volume and response time expectation included (TC18).
Concurrency, regression, and backward compatibility checks are present (TC20, TC21, TC22).
Date handling: malformed dates and full range inclusive tests are present (TC24, TC25, TC05).
Response content-type is asserted at least once and API documentation/error schema checks are present (TC01, TC28).
gaps: Pagination: No tests cover pagination parameters or behavior when the dataset exceeds a single page (page, limit, offsets, next/prev links, total counts).
Caching behavior: No assertions for cache headers such as ETag, Cache-Control, Last-Modified, or conditional GET/304 behavior.
Rate limiting/throttling: No tests for rate limits or 429 responses and Retry-After behavior.
Content-Type consistency: application/octet-stream is asserted only in TC01; most successful scenarios do not verify the content-type and that the octet stream payload can be parsed.
Boolean parameter validation: No negative tests for malformed boolean values (e.g., withHistory=notABool) or variations in boolean encoding.
RBAC / 403 Forbidden: No tests where a valid credential lacks admin privileges and should receive 403 (role/permission checks).
Invalid parameter combinations and edge cases: scenarios like minDate > maxDate, duplicate query params, conflicting filters, and parameter type mismatches are not covered.
Streaming semantics and large-response behavior beyond timing: chunked transfer, partial reads, memory usage under very large payloads, or confirmation of pagination vs streaming are not validated.
recommendations: Add pagination tests: verify page/limit/offset, results ordering across pages, total counts, and behavior when requesting beyond the last page.
Add caching tests: assert ETag and Cache-Control headers, test conditional GETs that should return 304, and confirm cache headers are appropriate for admin endpoints.
Add rate-limiting tests: simulate request floods to validate 429 responses, presence of Retry-After header, and graceful degradation under high request rates.
Assert application/octet-stream content-type in all successful scenarios and add tests to parse/deserialize the octet stream payload to validate returned entries.
Add parameter validation tests for boolean flags and other types (e.g., withHistory=xyz -> 400), and add tests for contradictory date ranges such as minDate > maxDate expecting a 400 error.
Add RBAC tests: valid token without admin role should produce 403; also test expired or malformed tokens producing 401.
Add negative/edge-case tests: duplicate query params, conflicting filters, timezone/date format variations, and inclusion/exclusion semantics for date ranges.
Add streaming/performance tests for extremely large result sets that validate chunking or pagination behavior and measure memory/throughput to avoid OOM on the client/server.
Broaden security fuzzing to cover injection/XSS across all parameters and assert no internal error details are leaked in responses.
Ensure all error responses (400/401/403/404/500/503/504) conform to a consistent error schema and add tests asserting that schema for each error case.
